## USER STORY WRITING STANDARDS

### Story Format (mandatory)
```
As a [specific user type — not "user"],
I want to [specific action],
So that [specific business/personal benefit].
```

### Acceptance Criteria Format (mandatory)
```
Given [initial context / state]
When [action is performed]
Then [expected system response]
And [additional assertion if needed]
```

### Story Sizing Guidance
- **Epic** — Large feature area (cannot be done in one sprint)
- **Story** — Completable in 1-3 days
- **Task** — Technical subtask under a story (no user value alone)
- If a story cannot be completed in 3 days → break it down further

### Anti-patterns (NEVER write stories like this)
❌ "As a user, I want a dashboard" — too vague, no benefit
❌ "The system shall display data" — not a user story, sounds like spec
❌ "User can do X and Y and Z" — too many things in one story
✅ "As a store manager, I want to see today's sales total at a glance, so that I can decide whether to run a promotion without opening a report"

---

## PRIORITY FRAMEWORK

### MoSCoW Method
| Priority | Label | Meaning |
|----------|-------|---------|
| P0 | **Must Have** | Launch blocker. App doesn't make sense without it. |
| P1 | **Should Have** | Core value. Include in v1 unless time/budget prevents. |
| P2 | **Could Have** | Nice-to-have. Drop if time is tight. |
| P3 | **Won't Have (now)** | Explicitly deferred. Documented to prevent scope creep. |

**Rule:** Never let client pressure move P2 items to P0 without timeline impact discussion.

